      <title>Predicate Generator</title>
      <link href="https://xallt.github.io/predicate-generator/"/>
      <updated>2018-05-31T00:00:00Z</updated>
      <id>https://xallt.github.io/predicate-generator/</id>
      <content type="html">
        <![CDATA[
      <p>This algorithm can be used to <strong>generate mathematical expressions</strong>.<br>
<em>Pretty cool, right?</em></p>
<p class="lp"><a class="lp-img lp-a" href="https://github.com/Xallt/PredicateGenerator" title="GitHub - Xallt/PredicateGenerator: ФД ФКН Project">
            <img class="lp-img" src="https://opengraph.githubassets.com/9cee71d376d51da42f130c268fd39d65edc2ef6cd620da4030db122b62adf5fc/Xallt/PredicateGenerator" data-src="https://opengraph.githubassets.com/9cee71d376d51da42f130c268fd39d65edc2ef6cd620da4030db122b62adf5fc/Xallt/PredicateGenerator" alt="GitHub - Xallt/PredicateGenerator: ФД ФКН Project" style="background: white">
        </a><a class="lp-met lp-a" href="https://github.com/Xallt/PredicateGenerator">
        <strong class="lp-ttl">GitHub - Xallt/PredicateGenerator: ФД ФКН Project<br></strong><em class="lp-dsc">ФД ФКН Project. Contribute to Xallt/PredicateGenerator development by creating an account on…</em><span class="lp-dom">github.com</span>
    </a>
</p>
<p>It's a generator of logical expressions with the ability to translate them to a given <em>language</em>.</p>
<h3>Examples</h3>
<p>All the output is translated to LaTeX:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th style="text-align:center"></th>
<th style="text-align:center"></th>
<th style="text-align:center"></th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style="text-align:center"><em>Basic</em></td>
<td style="text-align:center"><em>Mathematical</em></td>
<td style="text-align:center"><em>English</em></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="text-align:center"><img src="/images/predicate-generator/BasicScreenshot.png" alt="BasicScreenshot.png" ></td>
<td style="text-align:center"><img src="/images/predicate-generator/MathScreenshot.png" alt="MathScreenshot.png" ></td>
<td style="text-align:center"><img src="/images/predicate-generator/EngNaturalScreenshot.png" alt="EngNaturalScreenshot.png" ></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p>Adjacent expressions are similar because the algorithm outputs the lines in lexigraphic order</p>
<p>Here are actually interesting generated &quot;statements&quot; (not all of them are true)<br>
In this context variables are only non-negative integers</p>
<img src="/images/predicate-generator/MathFirstScreenshot.png" alt="MathFirstScreenshot.png" align="left" style="width: 40%;">
<p><strong>1)</strong> 2 is a prime number<br>
<strong>2)</strong> <del>Every single number is prime</del><br>
<strong>3)</strong> Prime numbers exist <strong>!</strong><br>
<strong>5)</strong> Every number is equal to itself<br>
<strong>6)</strong> There are numbers which are equal to themselves<br>
<strong>7)</strong> Not all numbers are prime<br>
<strong>8)</strong> <del>Prime numbers don't exist</del>\</p>

    ]]>
      </content>
